Distribution plots¶

In [131]:
plt.figure(figsize=(13,11))  
plt.subplot(3,2,1)
sns.kdeplot(df["speeding"],color="red")  
plt.subplot(3,2,2)
sns.kdeplot(df["alcohol"],color="green")  
plt.subplot(3,2,3)
sns.kdeplot(df["not_distracted"],color="blue")  
plt.subplot(3,2,4)
sns.kdeplot(df["no_previous"],color="orange")  
plt.subplot(3,2,5)
sns.kdeplot(df["ins_premium"],color="yellow")  
plt.subplot(3,2,6)
sns.kdeplot(df["ins_losses"],color="pink") 
plt.show()
first plot representing percentages of drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding are more between 3.8% and 4.7%¶
second plot representing the percentages of drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired are more between 3.9% and 4.3%¶
third plot representing the percentages of drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired are more ranging between 14.1% and 16.5%¶
fourth plot representing the Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Had Not Been Involved In Any Previous Accidents are more between 11.4% and 13.7%¶
fifth plot representing the Car Insurance Premiums per driver are more between 750 and 830¶
sixth plot representing the Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver are more between 137 and 155¶

Box plot¶

In [134]:
plt.figure(figsize=(17,15)) 
for i in range(1,len(df.columns)-1): 
    plt.subplot(3,2,i)
    sns.boxplot(df.iloc[:,i],color="orange") 
    plt.title(df.columns[i])
plt.show()
In first plot the distribution of percentages of drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding is left skewed¶
In second plot the distribution of percentages of drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired is slightly left skewed and has outliers¶
In third plot the distribution of Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Not Distracted is positively skewed¶
In fourth plot the distribution of Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Had Not Been Involved In Any Previous Accidents is perfectly symmetrical and has no outliers¶
In fifth plot the distribution of Car Insurance Premiums per driver is slightly left skewed¶
In sixth plot the distribution of Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver is slightly right skewed and has no outliers¶

Pie plot¶

In [135]:
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.pie([df[df["alcohol"]<5.0].shape[0],df[df["alcohol"]>=5.0].shape[0]], colors=["green","orange"],autopct="%1.2f%%") 
plt.title("alcohol")
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.pie([df[df["speeding"]<5.0].shape[0],df[df["speeding"]>=5.0].shape[0]],colors=["green","orange"], autopct="%1.2f%%") 
plt.title("speeding")  
plt.show()
first pie representing the percentage of states with less than 5% of drivers involved in collision due to alcohol is higher than percentage of states with greater than 5% of acidents drivers involved in collision due to alcohol¶
second pie representing the percentage of states with less than 5% of drivers involved in collision due to speeding is higher than percentage of states with greater than 5% of acidents drivers involved in collision due to speeding¶

Bar plot¶

In [136]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
plt.bar(["inspremium<750.0","750>=inspremium<1000.0","inspremium>=1000.0"],[df[df["ins_premium"]<750.0].shape[0], 
        df[(df["ins_premium"]>=750.0)&(df["ins_premium"]<1000.0)].shape[0], 
        df[df["ins_premium"]>1000.0].shape[0]]) 
plt.title("ins_premium") 
plt.show() 
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
plt.bar(["inslosses>75.0","75>=inslosses<100.0","inslosses>=100.0"],[df[df["ins_losses"]>75.0].shape[0], 
        df[(df["ins_losses"]>=75.0)&(df["ins_losses"]<100.0)].shape[0], 
        df[df["ins_losses"]>100.0].shape[0]]) 
plt.title("ins_losses") 
plt.show()
first plot representing insurance premium per driver is between 750 and 1000 has higher frequency¶
second plot representing that that insurance loss by company between 75 and 100 has less frequency comparitevely¶

Strip plot¶

In [137]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5)) 
sns.stripplot(data=df,x="low premium/high premium",y="ins_losses") 
plt.title("low premium/high premium vs ins_losses") 
plt.show()
from the plot we can observe that the drivers who pay insurance premiumns low are more than drivers who pay insurance premiumns high¶
And we can observe that loss incurred by company is high on drivers who pay insurance premiumns high¶
